This is one of several revolvers I bought brand new a few years ago around 2013 / 2014 primarily for my wife, who at the time was already comfortable with revolvers, but not yet very comfortable or proficient with my semi-auto Glocks (she tended to limp wrist and jam them.)  So in order to have some  guns around the home I knew that SHE could operate under duress if need be, I bought several versions of these simple but very sturdy Ruger revolvers for her to place around the home. With the exception of me test firing them once for functionality upon acquiring them (maybe 5 or 10 rounds each, that's it), they have all sat in drawers, or been hiding on shelves, or placed under beds, etc etc.  The point is that they are essentially brand new, with no wear, they were never holstered or even carried outside the home, they were test fired only once with less than 10 rounds,  and otherwise never used.  My wife has since become very proficient with my Glock semi-autos over the last few years (I'm a good teacher :) and is finally very comfortable with them as a go-to gun / crisis- in- the- house gun, so we don't see the need keeping all these revolvers around anymore.  So we have several revolvers like this to cut loose.  We've sold a few already, and have just a few more to unload.  These MSRP at over $800, they  retail in the brick and mortar stores in the high 600's to low 700's, and sell online anywhere from  600 to 625, plus shipping, CC fees, and FFL transfer agent fees.  We would let this go for $575 and eat the loss.  Even compared to an online Seller like on GB title: For Sale:  Winchester Pre-64 Model 70 30-06 Target Rifle
postcontent: For sale is this beautiful and rare Winchester Pre-64 Model 70 30-06 Target rifle.  This highly original, keenly accurate rifle was manufactured in July, 1957 and purchased by my grandfather new that same year in Johnstown, Pennsylvania.  My grandpa was a superb shot, a prize-winning target shooter, and a fan of the Winchester Model 70--he owned 6.  Unfortunately, he passed away in 1972 and I inherited this and a few other of his Models 70.  I don't think my grandfather shot this rifle for the last 5 years of his life and I've never shot it.  This magnificant rifle has been in a gun safe since 1972 and has only come out for its annual cleaning.  I'm only selling it because I could use the money for another project, so my loss is someone's gain.Again, this rifle is chambered in the venerable 30-06 Springfield and with a few exceptions I'll describe below, it's in factory condition.  The rifle is fitted with its original 24" heavy target barrel and the bore is bright with strong, crisp rifling.  Bluing is very nice with only edge wear.  The original Marksman stock is solid, wears the factory steel butt plate, and has no cracks or splits.  There are a few very minor scratches in the stock, consistent with a well-cared-for firearm that's 60 years old.  The rifle has quick-detachable scope bases, but no sights.  The action is as smooth as butter and the bolt is serialized to the action.  The rifle also has a trigger shoe and the trigger breaks cleanly and crisply.Here are the few things of note about the rifle.  The 3-position safety functions, but is a little sticky.  Grandpa cut a few shallow striations in the bolt handle for a better grip.  He also glass bedded the action and the first few inches of the barrel channel, and put some cross bolts in the stock for reinforcement.  Cross bolts are covered by wooden plugs and are nearly invisible.Except for the few nonstandard things I mentioned above, this is a highly original, very rare rifle that would be a tremendous addition to your shooting battery or firearms collection.  You won't find one of these for sale every day and Pre-64 rifles of this type have recently been selling for $2200.  I'm asking less to move it quickly.  I'd prefer to conduct a local exchange, but if someone who lives a substantial distance from Monument, CO would like the rifle I'm sure we can work something out.  Please feel free to contact me if you have questions.

stuff across all the various ammo sites I'm familiar with, and the average price per round for this specific ammo is typically 80-90 cents per round plus shipping, depending upon which website/ and which vendor.  The absolute cheapest major commercial vendors I could find were one or two entities selling around 77 cents, and one single random independent seller that was selling around 65 cents per round. So for sake of moving this stuff, as it will shortly be utterly valueless to me, I am willing to take a bath and sell these for 60 cents  a round for the whole lot, coming in cheaper than everybody, so call it $430. That's a savings to you of anywhere from 110 bucks to over 200 bucks, plus shipping,  depending upon which price figures we're using, but a definite savings to you nonetheless  Please do not ask to buy small quantities or split the batch in any way, or even haggle me down any further, as it's honestly not worth my time getting involved like that.  I'm discounting it heavily upfront right now to just get rid of it all at once, so if you have a 32 H&R Magnum revolver and want a lifetime supply of top quality ammo for it, you just got lucky.  My loss is your gain, I stocked up on this stuff around the time of the last ammo shortage hysteria 2 years ago, and I think I paid close to a buck a round at that time, maybe even more I hate to think.  But it is what it is, you win some and lose some. I got lucky this week discovering thru research that 3 of my earliest guns are actually fairly valuable collectibles these days, worth more now than I paid for them new, so you truly win some and lose some.  So I'm ok taking a little bath on this one, I'll make it up on my other sales . Please note this pricing is for a local sale, if I have to ship to you, I need to charge shipping, but will only charge the actual price with no markup for my time dragging it to UPS.

title: For Sale:  Rare Limited Production Smith and Wesson Airlite Ti 332 H&R Magnum
postcontent: This is a rare and valuable Smith and Wesson Airlite Ti (the "Ti" is for the titanium cylinder).  It's a J-frame, 6 shot revolver chambered in 32 H&R magnum.  I've had it for about 15 or 16 years, maybe it's even been 17 years.  I'm the original purchaser, I bought it at a gun shop in Miami Florida, but I just cant recall exactly which year I acquired this.  It was produced for only a limited time between 1999 and 2003, after which it was discontinued in 2004.  I'm pretty sure I acquired it around 1999 -2000 when I was still very early in my career,  but I'm waiting for Smith and Wesson to confirm that for me by the serial number. This was one of my backup pocket guns all these years, and to be totally candid, I was a bit shocked and surprised (pleasantly so) to discover this week through my research, that this was actually a valuable and pricey little gun for a pocket revolver.  I really had no idea frankly, and  had I known, I would have at least dusted it off and taken a better picture of it than I did :). I literally pulled it out of my pocket with all its built up pocket lint  and dust and fingerprints, and just snapped a quick pic, thinking this was probably just a $200 used gun.  But amazingly,  these things routinely sell for over $ 1,000 I've since learned.  Funny thing is I've always had a love hate relationship with this thing.  What I loved was that it was SUPERLIGHT thanks to the titanium cylinder, and carried 6 shots instead of 5, and was a nice smooth low recoil shooter.  What annoyed me was that sometimes spent cases tend to stick, and you have to poke them out with a pen or something.  SO anyway, Ive had this for all this time, it probably looks a bit rougher than it is bc I didn't bother to pretty it up at all before photographing it.  But it's actually seen very little actual use and has been shot not that much, it's just been carried a lot. Doubt if I have more than 250-300 rounds thru this thing, if that.  As for asking price, I'm going to wait until I hear from Smith and Wesson first on my purchase date, but I will entertain offers until then.  In the meantime, I'll wipe it down and take a cleaner pic.

title: For Sale:  9mm Beretta/Stoeger Cougar 8000
postcontent: For sale is my Beretta/Stoeger Cougar 8000 in 9mm INOX.  Handsome looking gun, very good SA 5.5 lb trigger, decent DA trigger.  I've got less than 200 rounds through it and it's been sitting in the safe for a year.This is an original Beretta design with the innovative rotating barrel which Beretta subsequently used on the PX4.  This was the next pistol after the 92 and is a more compact design than either the regular 92 or even 92 compact.  When Beretta decided to produce the PX4 in Italy they moved all the tooling and machinery to Turkey, put the Stoeger name on it (Stoeger is a subsidiary of Beretta) and essentially make the same Beretta gun in Turkey as they made in Italy.It's got a rail, ambi safety, dovetailed sights fore and aft, and a pleasantly aggressive set of grips.Asking $375 and buyer pays the transfer fee.   (Sound Loans in Everett is $25, they are friendly and accomdating folks, and convenient.  However, if it's too far for fthe buyer to drive, I'm open to any other reasonably-distanced FFL.)  All the usual laws apply.
